'''David Charles Gooding''' (21 November 1947 – 13 December 2009) was Professor of History and Philosophy of Science and Director of the Science Studies Centre, at the University of Bath, UK .<ref>{{cite journal | last = Tweney | first = Ryan D. | title = Eloge: David Charles Gooding, 1947–2009 | journal = [[Isis (journal)|Isis]] | volume = 101 | issue = 3 | pages = 609–609 | publisher = [[University of Chicago Press]] via JSTOR | doi = 10.1086/657172 | date = September 2010 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1086/657172 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref> He was President of the History of Science Section of the [[British Science Association|BAAS]] (2002–2003).

== Career ==
For over 30 years Gooding wrote and lectured on the role of visualisation, inference, communication, creativity and human agency in the sciences and was a specialist on the life and work of [[Michael Faraday]].  During 2002–2003 he held a [[Leverhulme Trust|Leverhulme]] Research Fellowship for research on Visualisation in the Sciences.  From 1991 to 1993 he held a Research Leave Fellowship from the MRC-ESRC-SERC (Joint Research Councils Initiative on HCI-Cognitive Science) for research on Simulating Natural Intelligence.<ref>{{cite web | title = David C. Gooding (biography) |url=http://gooding.socialpsychology.org/|publisher=Social Psychology Network|date=16 January 2008 }}</ref>

Gooding's work is characterised by a multi-disciplinary approach, combining perspectives and methods from different fields including philosophy, history, sociology, art and cognitive psychology. Gooding's notion of Construal is of key importance to the field of Empirical Modelling within Computer Science.<ref>{{cite book | last = Gooding | first = David | title = Experiment and the making of meaning: human agency in scientific observation and experiment | publisher = Kluwer Academic Publishers | location = Dordrecht, Netherlands | year = 1990 | isbn = 9780792307198 }} [http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/dcs/research/em/wj_re_em/construalgooding/ Excerpt: David Gooding's notion of construal, Department of Computer Science, University of Warwick.]</ref>

