{{short description|Identity management system}} {{cleanup rewrite|date=December 2017}} {{Advert|date=November 2018}}
{{Infobox software | name = FreeIPA | logo = https://www.freeipa.org/images/freeipa/freeipa-logo-small.png | screenshot = | caption = | developer = [[Red Hat]] | latest_release_version = 4.7.0<ref name="Releases/4.7.0 - FreeIPA">[https://www.freeipa.org/page/Releases/4.7.0 FreeIPA 4.7.0 Release Announcement]</ref> | latest_release_date = {{Start date and age|2018|07|19|df=yes}} | latest_preview_version = | latest_preview_date = | programming language = [[C (programming language)|C]]<ref>[http://freeipa.org/page/Coding_Style C Coding Style - Free IPA]</ref> and [[Python (programming language)|Python]]<ref>[http://freeipa.org/page/Python_Coding_Style Python Coding Style - Free IPA]</ref> | operating_system = Linux / [[Unix]] | genre = [[Identity management]] | license = [[GNU General Public License]] | website = [http://www.freeipa.org/ www.freeipa.org] }}
'''FreeIPA''' is an [[Identity management system]]. It aims to provide an easily managed [[identity management|Identity]], [[Computer security policy|Policy]], and [[audit trail|Audit]] (IPA) system.<ref>
{{cite book | last1 = Negus | first1 = Christopher | last2 = Foster-Johnson | first2 = Eric | title = Fedora Bible 2011 Edition: Featuring Fedora Linux 14 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=VWc9dmHLVssC | location = Indianapolis | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | publication-date = 2011 | isbn = 9781118085738 | accessdate = 2016-09-01 | quote = The "IPA" part of FreeIPA stands for identity (identifying and authenticating users and machines), policy (settings for access control of applications and machines), and audit (methods for collecting and auditing security events, logs, and user activities). }} </ref> FreeIPA is the [[Upstream (software development)|upstream]] [[open-source software|open-source]] project for [[Red Hat|Red Hat Identity Manager]].<ref>[https://developers.redhat.com/blog/2016/04/29/red-hat-identity-manager-part-1-overview-and-getting-started/ Red Hat Identity Manager: Part 1 – Overview and Getting started]</ref>
== Features ==
* Integrated security information management solution combining Linux (Fedora), 389 Directory Server, MIT Kerberos, NTP, DNS, Dogtag certificate system, SSSD and others. * Built on top of well known Open Source components and standard protocols * Strong focus on ease of management and automation of installation and configuration tasks. * Full multi master replication for higher redundancy and scalability * Extensible management interfaces (CLI, Web UI, XMLRPC and JSONRPC API) and Python SDK
{{As of | 2018}} FreeIPA uses [[389 Directory Server]] for its [[LDAP]] implementation, MIT's [[Kerberos (protocol)|Kerberos 5]] for authentication and [[single sign-on]], the [[Apache HTTP Server]] and [[Python (programming language)|Python]] for the [[management framework]] and [[Web user interface|Web UI]], (optionally) [[DogTag]]<ref> {{cite web |url= http://pki.fedoraproject.org/ |title= Home page for the Dogtag Certificate System |date= 2015-01-20 |accessdate= 2015-01-20 }} </ref> for the integrated [[Certificate authority|CA]], and [[BIND]] with a custom plugin for the integrated [[Domain Name System|DNS]] server. Since version 3.0.0, FreeIPA also uses [[Samba (software)|Samba]] to integrate with [[Microsoft]]'s [[Active directory|Active Directory]] by way of Cross Forest Trusts.
Each of the major components of FreeIPA operates as a pre-existing Free-Software/Open-Source project, the bundling of these components into a single manageable suite with a comprehensive management interface is GPLv3, but that does not change the licences of the components.
FreeIPA aims to provide support not just for Linux- and Unix-based computers, but ultimately also for [[Microsoft Windows]] and Apple [[OS X]] computers.
