{{Infobox scholar | name = Graham M. Smith | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | fullname = | othernames = | birth_name = Graham M. Smith | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | era = | region = | nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] | alma_mater = | school_tradition = | main_interests = Friendship and the Political | principal_ideas = | major_works = | awards = | influences = | influenced = | footnotes = | relatives = | spouse = | children = }}
'''Graham M. Smith''' is a British [[political theorist]]. Currently he is a lecturer at [[University of Leeds]]. Smith is known for his research on [[friendship]] and its relation to the understanding of the political. He previously taught at [[Lancaster University]] and is the co-editor of the online, peer-reviewed, open-access journal ''[[AMITY: The Journal of Friendship Studies]]''.<ref>[http://eprints.soas.ac.uk/17937/ Friendship Matters]</ref><ref>[http://amityjournal.leeds.ac.uk/people/ AMITY] </ref><ref>[http://www.bloomsbury.com/author/graham-m-smith Graham M. Smith]</ref><ref>[http://www.bloomsbury.com/uk/confronting-secularism-in-europe-and-india-9781474269223/ Confronting Secularism in Europe and India]</ref>
==Works== * ''Confronting Secularism in Europe and India: Legitimacy and Disenchantment in Contemporary Times'' (co-edited with [[Brian Black (philosopher)|Brian Black]] and [[Gavin Hyman]]), Bloomsbury (2014). * ''Friendship and the Political: Kierkegaard, Nietzsche, Schmitt'', Imprint Academic, (2011). * ''Friendship in Politics: Theorizing Amity In and Between States'' (ed. with [[Preston Theodore King]]), Routledge, (2008). * ‘Friendship, State and Nation’ in ''Friendship and International Relations'', eds. Koschut, S. and Oelsner, A. (2014) * ‘Kierkegaard, Søren’ in ''Encyclopaedia of Political Theory'', ed. Bevir, Mark, Sage, (2010).
